\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Virtual Reality (VR) immerses users in a fully digital environment, providing an interactive and immersive experience through the use of headsets, motion sensors, and controllers. VR technology is used in gaming, training simulations, education, and therapy. By creating realistic and engaging virtual worlds, VR enables users to experience scenarios that would be difficult or impossible in the real world. Key components of VR systems include high-resolution displays, spatial audio, and haptic feedback. The continuous advancement of VR technology is driven by improvements in graphics processing, motion tracking, and content creation tools, expanding its applications and accessibility.}